Prosper Loans Data Exploration¶

by (Joseph Osuntoki)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The aim of this project is to use Python data science and data visualization libraries to explore the dataset’s variables and understand the data’s structure, oddities, patterns, and relationships.

  • The dataset has 113937 observations and 81 variables
  • For the purpose of this analysis, I selected only the variables that'd help understand the data better

  • Possible variables of interest are : Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, EstimatedReturn, ProsperRating, ProsperRating, ListingCategory, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus, and some others.

  • I identified 20 variables that carry the potential of unleashing the most pertinent insights in the dataset.

NB: I spent a couple of hours reading the variable description here, going through the dataset visually (in Excel), and selected those 20 features for the purpose of this analysis. I also dropped some features becasue of they contain many missing values (>70%), some have many zeros - as shown in the analysis performed above

  • Having just 20 variables would speed up our analysis, make it less cumbersome, and foster better understanding.

The values in the CreditGrade column are the missing values in Prosper Rating(Alpha) column

Combine the two columns together and drop one of them

loan_data['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = loan_data['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].combine_first(loan_data['CreditGrade'])

obj = loan_data.columns[loan_data.dtypes==object]

        loan_data[i].fillna(loan_data[i].mode()[0], inplace = True)

numeric = loan_data.columns[loan_data.dtypes!=object]

for i in numeric:

Define¶

Issue #4¶

The data type of the listing category is int64 which shouldn't be. According to the variable description, each number represents a particular category.

Also, the abbreviations used in the BorrowerState feature are not descriptive enough.

Define¶

Replace the integers with their repective categories. And the abbreviations with their respective state names.

Issue #5¶

Variables such as "BorrowerAPR","EstimatedReturn", and "BankcardUtilization" should be in percentages.

Define¶

Multiply the features by 100 to convert to percentage. We need the features to retain the float type which is why we are not using the ".format" method.

Code¶

In [24]:
loan_data["BorrowerAPR"] = round(loan_data["BorrowerAPR"]*100,1)
loan_data["EstimatedReturn"] = round(loan_data["EstimatedReturn"]*100,1)
loan_data["BankcardUtilization"] = round(loan_data["BankcardUtilization"]*100,1)

def relative_bar(data):
    count = loan_data[data].value_counts()
    order = count.index
    
    n_ = loan_data[data].value_counts().sum()
    max_count = count[0]
    max_prop = max_count / n_
    # establish tick locations and create plot
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    ticks = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.05)
    tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (8,8));
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0];
    ax = sb.countplot(data=loan_data, y= data, color = base_color, order = order);
    plt.xticks(ticks * n_, tick_names)
    plt.xlabel('Proportion')
    plt.ylabel(data + " Values")
    plt.title('Proportion of each unique value in the ' + data + " feature")

For the univariate explorations, the following were discovered:

  • People took most of the loans for debt consolidation...About 50% of the borrowers borrowed to consolidate debt. Only about 7% took loans for business purposes
  • The top five states represented are CA - California, TX - Texas, NY - New York, FL - Florida, IL - Illinois
  • About 48% of the loans are still in payment.
  • Most of the borrowers are rated C (which is low-grade); this means the credit agency took more risk than normal.
  • The monthly income particularly had some outliers, which was why I used the xlim parameter.
  • The monthly income feature is skewed to the right while the principal feature is multi-modal
  • The Principal feature looked more "Normal" after a log transformation was applied
  • The credit agency had negative returns on some loans due to incomplete payment. But only 195 of them resulted in negative returns
  • More than 30% of the loans were listed in 2013 and it's by far greater than other years in the data.
  • There doesn't seem to be any particular quarter that favors loan disbursements.

def heat_values(col):
    ct_counts = loan_data.groupby(['LoanStatus', col]).size()
    ct_counts = ct_counts.reset_index(name='count')
    ct_counts = ct_counts.pivot(index = 'LoanStatus', columns = col, values = 'count')
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])
    sb.heatmap(ct_counts,annot = True, fmt = '.0f')
    plt.title('Heatmap showing relationship between Loan Status and ' + col)

def biv_bar(data):
    count = loan_data['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
    order = count.index
    
    n_ = loan_data['LoanStatus'].value_counts().sum()
    max_count = count[0]
    max_prop = max_count / n_
    # establish tick locations and create plot
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    ticks = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.05)
    tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,8));
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0];
    ax = sb.countplot(data=loan_data, x= 'LoanStatus', hue = data, order = order);
    plt.yticks(ticks * n_, tick_names)
    plt.xlabel("Percentage of " + data + " Represented")
    plt.ylabel("Loan Status")
    plt.title('Relationship of LoanStatus with the ' + data + " feature")
    ax.legend(loc = 1, framealpha = 1)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

By far, the employed ones who took more loans than the other categories

For the bivariate explorations, the following were discovered:

  • The employed ones who took more loans than those in the other categories
  • The ones rated very high had low bank card utilzation. the ones rated low (C,D,E,and HR) had higher bank card utilization. This is not strange as it suggest that they took loans more often
  • There is a positive relationship between the Annual Percentage Rate on the loan and return on the loan for the credit agency.
  • C,D, E, and HR rated borrowers defaulted the most. The lower the rating, the higher the risk of default.
  • Most loans currently in payment were borrowed by C-rated client

In [79]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loan_data, row = 'Rating', size = 3, margin_titles = False)
g.map(plt.scatter,'Return','APR');

It becomes very clear now that the loans that resulted in negative returns for the credit agency were borrowed by HR-rated borrowers which is the lowest grade. They had the highest APR as well, which is not strange as the APR compensates for the risk the agency takes by issuing the loan. In summary, this means the lower your rating, the more the APR and the more the likelihood of default.

For the mulitvariate explorations, the following were discovered:

  • The lower the rating, the more the APR and the more the likelihood of default.
  • Borrowers rated B, C and D yielded the highest returns for the credit agency
  • It doesn't seem that monthly income determines the quality of borrowers' credit rating. The same thing goes with work_duration. Those who had worked for long didnt necesarily have good credit ratings
  • Borrowers who are homeonwers are likely to have a higher monthly income
  • The unemployed ones have small work duration and little revolving credit balance
  • The biggest loans were listed in 2013 and 2014

Conclusions¶

  • People took most of the loans for debt consolidation...About 50% of the borrowers borrowed to consolidate debt. Only about 7% took loans for business purposes
  • The top five states represented are CA - California, TX - Texas, NY - New York, FL - Florida, IL - Illinois
  • About 48% of the loans are still in payment.
  • Most of the borrowers are rated C (which is low-grade); this means the credit agency took more risk than normal.
  • The monthly income particularly had some outliers, which was why I used the xlim parameter.
  • The monthly income feature is skewed to the right while the principal feature is multi-modal
  • The Principal feature looked more "Normal" after a log transformation was applied
  • The credit agency had negative returns on some loans due to incomplete payment. But only 195 of them resulted in negative returns
  • More than 30% of the loans were listed in 2013 and it's by far greater than other years in the data.
  • There doesn't seem to be any particular quarter that favors loan disbursements.
  • The employed ones who took more loans than those in the other categories
  • The ones rated very high had low bank card utilzation. the ones rated low (C,D,E,and HR) had higher bank card utilization. This is not strange as it suggest that they took loans more often
  • There is a positive relationship between the Annual Percentage Rate on the loan and return on the loan for the credit agency.
  • C,D, E, and HR rated borrowers defaulted the most. The lower the rating, the higher the risk of default.
  • Most loans currently in payment were borrowed by C-rated client
  • The lower the rating, the more the APR and the more the likelihood of default.
  • Borrowers rated B, C and D yielded the highest returns for the credit agency
  • It doesn't seem that monthly income determines the quality of borrowers' credit rating. The same thing goes with work_duration. Those who had worked for long didnt necesarily have good credit ratings
  • Borrowers who are homeonwers are likely to have a higher monthly income
  • The unemployed ones have small work duration and little revolving credit balance
  • The credit agency has issued bigger loans than usual in 2013 and 2014. Before then, loans barely crosssed the 25000 mark
  • The agency started issuing different term loans in 2010 and in 2014 particularly, has only issued loans with >=36 months maturity
